1326–1352","1352–1385":"1352–1385","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1351":"1351","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Shrivenham, Berkshire, England":"Shrivenham, Berkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bunn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Bone  .","German: perhaps from   Bunde   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Bun","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Cambodian Leng, Sun, Chhay, Chheng, Han, Heng, In, Khin, Khun, Pin, Seng, Yeng, Phon, Thy, Loeung, Pheng, Savuth, Thoeun, Boeun, Bopha, Chhorn, Hak, Ly, Minh, Saroeun, Than, Thong, Thoung, Phorn, Samoeun, Savoeun, Soeun, Soeung, Sokheng, Yoeum.","Cambodian: written ប៊ុន, unexplained.","English: variant of   Bunn   (see   Bone  )."]},{"name":"Bone","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname meaning ‘good’, from Middle English <i>bon(e)</i>, <i>boun</i>, Old French <i>bon</i> ‘good’.","English: possibly a nickname from Middle English <i>bone</i> ‘bone, leg’ (Old English <i>bān</i>; compare   Bain   3), used of someone with a bad leg or long legs.","English: variant of   Boone   1."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"May","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of both   Margaret   and   Mary .  The popularity of this name, which was at its height in the early 20th century, has been reinforced by the fact that it fits into the series of month names with   April   and   June  , and also belongs to the group of flower names, being another word for the hawthorn, whose white flowers blossom in May. It is now not much used independently but is a common component of compounds such as <i>Ella-May</i>, <i>Lily-May</i>, and <i>Daisy-May</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret May Bunn was born in 1330, in Berkshire, England, her father, Sir Bunn, was 31 and her mother, Lady Bunn, was 26. She married Henry Loveday in 1351, in Shrivenham, Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1352, in Shrivenham, Berkshire, England, at the age of 22, and was buried in Berkshire, England."},"et":{"1330–1352":"1330–1352","1326–1352":"1326–1352","1352–1385":"1352–1385","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1351":"1351","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Shrivenham, Berkshire, England":"Shrivenham, Berkshire, England"},"fi":{"1330–1352":"1330–1352","1326–1352":"1326–1352","1352–1385":"1352–1385","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1305–Female":"1305–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1351":"1351","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Shrivenham, Berkshire, England":"Shrivenham, Berkshire, England"},"fr":{"1330–1352":"1330–1352","1326–1352":"1326–1352","1352–1385":"1352–1385","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1305–Female":"1305–Décédée","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1351":"1351","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, Angleterre","Shrivenham, Berkshire, England":"Shrivenham, Berkshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Margaret May Bunn est née en 1330, à Berkshire, Angleterre, son père, Sir Bunn, avait 31 ans et sa mère, Lady Bunn, avait 26 ans. Elle a épousé Henry Loveday en 1351, à Shrivenham, Berkshire, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée en 1352, à Shrivenham, Berkshire, Angleterre, à l’âge de 22 ans, et a été enterrée à Berkshire, Angleterre."},"de":{"1330–1352":"1330–1352","1326–1352":"1326–1352","1352–1385":"1352–1385","1300–Male":"1300–Verstorben","1305–Female":"1305–Verstorben","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1351":"1351","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Shrivenham, Berkshire, England":"Shrivenham, Berkshire, England","lifeSummary":"Als Margaret May Bunn 1330 in Berkshire, England geboren wurde, war ihr Vater Sir Bunn 31 und ihre Mutter Lady Bunn 26. Sie hat 1351 in Shrivenham, Berkshire, England Henry Loveday geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb 1352 im Alter von 22 Jahren in Shrivenham, Berkshire, England und wurde in Berkshire, England begraben."},"ht":{"1330–1352":"1330–1352","1326–1352":"1326–1352","1352–1385":"1352–1385","1300–Male":"1300–Desede","1305–Female":"1305–Desede","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1351":"1351","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Shrivenham, Berkshire, England":"Shrivenham, Berkshire, England"},"hu":{"1330–1352":"1330–1352","1326–1352":"1326–1352","1352–1385":"1352–1385","1300–Male":"1300–elhunyt","1305–Female":"1305–elhunyt","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1351":"1351","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Shrivenham, Berkshire, England":"Shrivenham, Berkshire, England"},"id":{"1330–1352":"1330–1352","1326–1352":"1326–1352","1352–1385":"1352–1385","1300–Male":"1300–Telah Meninggal","13